lookup.term:
{Soil_does_NOT_remain_in_ball_when_squeezed}

          Place approximately 25 g soil in palm. Add water dropwise and knead the soil to break down all aggregates. Soil is at the proper consistency when plastic and moldable, like moist putty.


            {Is_too_dry}

            The soil sample is too dry.


              NO RESULT: Add more water and start again




          {Is_too_wet}

            The soil sample is too wet.


              NO RESULT: Add dry soil and start again

              NO RESULT: add dry soil to soak up water



          {NOT_too_wet_nor_too_dry}

            The soil is NOT too wet nor too dry.


              {Sand}

              A sand has a loose gritty feel and does not stick together. Individual sand grains can be seen or felt. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)

{Soil_remains_in_ball_when_squeezed}

          Place approximately 25 g soil in palm. Add water dropwise and knead the soil to break down all aggregates. Soil is at the proper consistency when plastic and moldable, like moist putty.


            {TASK:_Roll_ribbon}

            Rub a ball of soil between thumb and forefinger to make a 'ribbon'


              {Does_NOT_form_a_ribbom}

              A 'ribbon' is NOT formed when a ball of soil is rubbed between thumb and forefinger.


                {Loamy_Sand}

                In a loamy sand particles barely stick together and a moulded piece of soil just holds its shape. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)



            {Forms_ribbon}

              A 'ribbon' is formed when a ball of soil is rubbed between thumb and forefinger.


                {Medium_ribbon_(2.5-5cm_long)}

                The ribbon formed when a ball of soil is rubbed between thumb and forefinger is between 2.5 and 5cm long.


                  {TASK:_Wet_soil_and_rub_with_forefinger}

                  Excessively wet a small pinch of soil in palm and rub with forefinger.


                    {Does_NOT_feel_very_gritty}

                    The wetted soil does NOT feel very gritty when rubbed on the palm and with forefinger.


                      {Feels_very_smooth}

                      The wetted soil feels very smooth when rubbed on the palm and with forefinger.


                        {Silty_Clay_Loam}

                        A silty clay loam is like a clay loam but silty as well and smooth to the touch. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)



                    {Neither_very_gritty_nor_very_smooth}

                      The wetted soil does NOT feel very smooth nor very gritty when rubbed on the palm and with forefinger.


                        {Clay_Loam}

                        More easily moulded into a shape than a loam, a clay loam rolls out to a thin ribbon between the palms while a loam will break-up. When dry a clay loam will form a lump but is not as tough to break as a clay.(VDEPI 2009: AG0058)




                  {Feels_very_gritty}

                    The wetted soil feels very gritty when rubbed on the palm and with forefinger.


                      {Sandy_Clay_Loam}

                      A sandy clay loam is like a clay loam but sand grains can be felt (and heard - see Sandy Loam) (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)





              {Strong_ribbon}

                The ribbon formed when a ball of soil is rubbed between thumb and forefinger is strong and over 5cm long.


                  {TASK:_Wet_soil_and_rub_with_forefinger}

                  Excessively wet a small pinch of soil in palm and rub with forefinger.


                    {Does_NOT_feel_very_gritty}

                    The wetted soil does NOT feel very gritty when rubbed on the palm and with forefinger.


                      {Feels_very_smooth}

                      The wetted soil feels very smooth when rubbed on the palm and with forefinger.


                        {Silty_Clay}

                        A silty clay is like a clay but smoother. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)



                    {Neither_very_gritty_nor_very_smooth}

                      The wetted soil does NOT feel very smooth nor very gritty when rubbed on the palm and with forefinger.


                        {Clay}

                        Clays are tough and can be moulded into shapes when moist. Clays form a long flexible ribbon when rubbed between the palms and the ribbon can often be bent into a U shape without breaking. Clays dry into very hard clods. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)




                  {Feels_very_gritty}

                    The wetted soil feels very gritty when rubbed on the palm and with forefinger.


                      {Sandy_Clay}

                      A sandy clay is like a clay but sand grains can be felt (and heard - see Sandy Loam). (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)





              {Weak_ribbon_(Less_than_2.5cm_long)}

                The ribbon formed when a ball of soil is rubbed between thumb and forefinger is less than 2.5cm long.


                  {TASK:_Wet_soil_and_rub_with_forefinger}

                  Excessively wet a small pinch of soil in palm and rub with forefinger.


                    {Does_NOT_feel_very_gritty}

                    The wetted soil does NOT feel very gritty when rubbed on the palm and with forefinger.


                      {Feels_very_smooth}

                      The wetted soil feels very smooth when rubbed on the palm and with forefinger.


                        {Silt_Loam}

                        A silty loam is like a loam but has a smooth silky feel when a moist sample is pushed between the index finger and thumb. On drying a sample can form a hard lump but this may be broken by hand. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)



                    {Neither_very_gritty_nor_very_smooth}

                      The wetted soil does NOT feel very smooth nor very gritty when rubbed on the palm and with forefinger.


                        {Loam}

                        A loam breaks into crumbs but will tend to stick together. Sand grains cannot be felt in a moist sample which when squeezed will retain its shape when handled freely. Loams are usually soft to the feel. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)




                  {Feels_very_gritty}

                    The wetted soil feels very gritty when rubbed on the palm and with forefinger.


                      {Sandy_Loam}

                      A sandy loam sticks together more than a loamy sand but can be easily broken. Individual sand grains can be felt and heard if a wet sample is rubbed between the index finger and thumb and held close to the ear. (VDEPI 2009: AG0058)

{Brick}

          Fired or sun-dried clay block used in masonry construction.


            {Dry-pressed}
            Dry pressed brick 

          {Glazed_brick}


          {Sandstock}
            Hand-made colonial bricks

{Stone}

          Worked or unworked stone used in masonry walls.


            {Ashlar}
            Finely dressed stone with flat face.


          {Other}


          {Roughly-hewn}
            Roughly cut stone: shows some sign of shaping.


          {Rubble}
            Stone fragments with few signs of shaping

{Timber}

          Timber uprights or other elements for a wall or fence.


            {Beam}
            Timber beam or support.


          {Plank}
            Timber plank for flooring or panelling. 

          {Post}
            Round or square timber post.

{Mortar}

          Paste used to bind masonry blocks together. 

            {Cement_mortar}
            Cement based mortar


          {Lime-shell_mortar}
            Sandy mortar with lime and burnt shell inlcusion

{Brick}



            {English_Bond}
            Full courses of headers alternating with full courses of stretchers.


          {Flemish_Bond}
            Courses of alternating headers and stretchers.


          {Header_Bond}
            Courses of headers only. 

          {Stretcher}
            Courses of full bricks where every course is offset half a brick from the course below.

{Stone}



            {Quoins_stressed}
            Large corner blocks set along side regular courses blocks.


          {Random_coursed}
            Patterning of different shaped, rubble stone.


          {Random_uncoursed}
            No regular pattern


          {Regular_courses}
            Lines or courses of regular size.


          {String_courses}
            Long stones in regular lines or courses.


          {Uneven_courses}
            Lines or courses of different size
